    {
        "content": "<p>There are a collection of definitions around bundles that I seem able to relate correctly with my intuition. However, I'm pretty sure there is an abstract principle governing everything, but I'm struggling to smoke it out.</p>\n<p>I'll attempt a question, but if someone can see I'm circling a big idea I'd appreciate it if they pointed it out.</p>\n<p>Subobject classifiers are special, because maps into them correspond to subobjects. You can expand the congruence <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(X) \\cong \\textrm{hom}(X, \\Omega)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> into the pullback diagram:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/OMU9BjcKkXxyFcSdBKyAL2YB/image.png\">Subobject classifier</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/OMU9BjcKkXxyFcSdBKyAL2YB/image.png\" title=\"Subobject classifier\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"482x443\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/OMU9BjcKkXxyFcSdBKyAL2YB/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>In Set, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> is just the boolean set.</p>\n<p>In type theory, it's useful to imagine <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">{</mo><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">{</mo><mo>⋅</mo><mo fence=\"true\">}</mo></mrow><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">{</mo><mo fence=\"true\">}</mo></mrow><mo fence=\"true\">}</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega = \\left \\{ \\left \\{ \\cdot \\right \\}, \\left \\{ \\right \\} \\right \\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">{</span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">⋅</span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">}</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">{</span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">}</span></span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">}</span></span></span></span></span>, or even to think of our classifying function, or predicate, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>χ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\chi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span></span></span></span> as a map into Set that returns the inputs  wrapped in a set if they're in the subset, and empty otherwise.</p>\n<p>With that change, then our subset is given by the category of elements <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo><mi>χ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int \\chi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span></span></span></span>. It's just the union of all the preimages.</p>\n<p>This seems to be a kind of special case of the universal construction relating set valued functions, and bundles. Given by the following diagram:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/m1sw2fFwKQTc2IRwaTjFg16U/image.png\">Bundle classifier</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/m1sw2fFwKQTc2IRwaTjFg16U/image.png\" title=\"Bundle classifier\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"428x407\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/m1sw2fFwKQTc2IRwaTjFg16U/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>It's harder to write the natural congruence here in a way that captures the use of the category of elements, in a sort of fake math notation, it'd look something like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>≅</mo><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>∫</mo><mi>F</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> F : [B, Set] \\cong \\textrm{hom}(\\int F, B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>There's some story here involving \"Stuff, Structure, and properties\" and categorification. I'm not sure why the category of elements is involved beyond it \"unions the sets\". In this diagram it's describing a limit, but unions are usually colimits, like coends.</p>\n<p>To ground this with a definite question though, is there a way to indicate what properties the fibers should satisfy by modifying the diagram? It's clear the subobject classifier classifies injective maps, because the fibers have at most one element - If they also had at least one element they'd be isomorphisms. Is there a way to take the pullback defining Set, and tweak it to require the output sets are at best singletons, and then see the new diagram must be the pullback of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span>? </p>\n<p>And again if there is some more abstract idea that explains how everything is related, like maybe grothendieck constructions, I'm open to any explanation or pointers to places to learn more.</p>",
        "id": 568128821,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1768455564
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>...And now that I just wrote that out, it occurs to me that in the diagram for the subobject classifier, with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> being the simple minded bool, the predicate <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Chi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">X</span></span></span></span> has the features of a bundle, with its preimage giving <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>, an object which then embeds into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> via the monomorphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>. This monomorphism has the character of a generalized element.</p>\n<p>But when we step up from arrows to functors when looking at the pullback describing Set, their roles are reversed. The indexing functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> looks like a generalized element picking out sets from Set, with it being wrapped into a bundle into B from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Is there something mathematical going on here, or are \"generalized elements\" and \"bundles\" just points of view?</p>",
        "id": 568133197,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1768458646
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just as the subobject classifier classifies subobjects via pullback, the forgetful functor from pointed sets to sets classifies <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/discrete%20opfibrations\">[[discrete opfibrations]]</a>. The idea that Set plays the role of a categorified subobject classifier is explored in detail in Weber's paper <a href=\"https://webercat.au/2topos.pdf\">Yoneda structures from 2-toposes</a>.</p>",
        "id": 568144535,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1768464839
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The pattern you're noticing, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277352\">@Alex Kreitzberg</span>, is very broad.  I wrote about some examples in <a href=\"http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/week223.html\">week223</a> of <em>This Week's Finds</em>, and in a more formal way in the start of <a href=\"http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/cohomology.pdf\">Lectures on n-categories and cohomology</a>.</p>\n<p>Here are some stuff quoted from week223, given examples of the principle you're noticing:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>n-GROUPOIDS FIBERED OVER AN n-GROUPOID B ARE \"THE SAME\" AS<br>\nWEAK (n+1)-FUNCTORS FROM B TO THE (n+1)-GROUPOID nGpd</p>\n<p>Grothendieck also studied this kind of thing with categories replacing groupoids, so there should also be an n-category version, I think... but it's more delicate to define \"fibrations\" for categories than for groupoids, so I'm a bit scared to state a slogan suitable for n-categories.</p>\n<p>However, I'm not scared to go from n-groupoids to ω-groupoids, which are basically the same as spaces. In terms of spaces, the slogan goes like this:</p>\n<p>SPACES FIBERED OVER THE SPACE B ARE \"THE SAME\" AS MAPS FROM B TO THE SPACE OF ALL SPACES</p>\n<p>This is how James Dolan taught it to me. Most mortals are scared of \"the space of all spaces\" - both for fear of Russell's paradox, and because we really need a <em>space</em> of all spaces, not just a mere set of them. To avoid these terrors, you can water down Jim's slogan by choosing a specific space F to be the fiber:</p>\n<p>FIBRATIONS WITH FIBER F OVER THE SPACE B ARE \"THE SAME\" AS MAPS FROM B TO THE CLASSIFYING SPACE OF AUT(F)</p>\n<p>where AUT(F) is the topological group of homotopy self-equivalences of F. The fearsome \"space of all spaces\" is then the disjoint union of the classifying spaces of all these topological groups AUT(F). It's too large to be a space unless you pass to a larger universe of sets, but otherwise it's perfectly fine. Grothendieck invented the notion of a \"Grothendieck universe\" for precisely this purpose.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This was written before homotopy type theory came into being.  These ideas can be stated more cleanly in that framework.</p>",
        "id": 568283904,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1768501255
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It sounds like a vast generalisation of what I was talking about in my “Indexed-Fibred Duality” article…</p>",
        "id": 568284091,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruby Khondaker (she/her)",
        "timestamp": 1768501322
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm still processing the answers, but I do want to acknowledge Ruby's questions and articles around similar (the same?) topic have been helpful. My accordion post from even earlier touched on similar ideas from a much more confused perspective. In retrospect I see you can lift abstract intervals to concrete intervals on the accordion layout, which I believe means an accordion is an example of a fibration. With the projection sending pitches to their letter names, and physical intervals to their musical intervals.</p>\n<p>But I still felt something was missing, so I wanted to start a thread to see if the way I phrased my confusion would invite answers relevant to my confusion.</p>",
        "id": 568289815,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1768503400
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess to apply Baez's slogan to accordion layouts - a specific accordion layout is \"the same\" as all of the possible transpositions of melodies expressed in terms of intervals. If I'm understanding all the moving parts of the above correctly.</p>\n<p>I think that's even the same as the groupoid version of the statement, because the layout is even a torsor (if you pretend the accordion is infinite).</p>\n<p>It's good to know homotopy type theory is a nice way to think about this.</p>\n<p>Lets see if I can say something interesting, or have questions, about Weber's paper.</p>",
        "id": 568316931,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1768513631
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Bundles.20and.20object.20classifiers/near/568283904\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The pattern you're noticing, @Alex Kreitzberg, is very broad. I wrote about some examples in <a href=\"http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/week223.html\">week223</a> of <em>This Week's Finds</em>, and in a more formal way in the start of <a href=\"http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/cohomology.pdf\">Lectures on n-categories and cohomology</a>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I had seen this some time ago but had forgotten about it. In this perspective, what does one make of, more generally, sequences? What I have in mind are, for example, those four-term sequences <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>W</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">W \\to X \\to Y \\to Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> appearing in the construction of the Toda bracket.</p>",
        "id": 568515213,
        "sender_full_name": "Alonso Perez-Lona",
        "timestamp": 1768594182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know.</p>",
        "id": 568549882,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1768615631
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe this is a more simple minded question in that vein.</p>\n<p>The exact sequences are a nice way to specify the fibers are all isomorphic.</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1 \\rightarrow F \\rightarrow E \\rightarrow B \\rightarrow 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>I took this as an answer to my question of \"how do you specify the fibers of a bundle in a category?\" But as an exercise I was going to try to see if I could expand the exact sequence definition into a more abstract diagram or leave it to a future HoTT proof (for example, I remember there it's important to show all types in a family are contractible if you want a proposition).</p>\n<p>Maybe more experienced folks have suggestions for how to approach this as an exercise, or if it is a good exercise?</p>",
        "id": 568552927,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1768619076
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I got a ping that has me worried I asked the question poorly.</p>\n<p>I know I can find the fibers with pullbacks:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/cneuyZC43P6tr5vc9BziLDcI/1000021896\">Preimage via pullback</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/cneuyZC43P6tr5vc9BziLDcI/1000021896\" title=\"Preimage via pullback\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/jpeg\" data-original-dimensions=\"643x599\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/cneuyZC43P6tr5vc9BziLDcI/1000021896/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>I made up the exercises:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What could we add to the pullback diagram, so that given any <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" mathvariant=\"normal\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo>∈</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b, b' \\in B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9463em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> we have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>p</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><msup><mi>p</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" mathvariant=\"normal\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p^{-1}(b) \\cong p^{-1}(b')</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>? </li>\n<li>How are pullback diagrams related to exact sequences?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>My question to the room is, are these good solvable exercises?</p>\n<p>I wouldn't have asked but given Alonso's question, I thought maybe asking would help open the door to talk about exact sequences for a bit.</p>",
        "id": 568571284,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1768638723
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277352\">Alex Kreitzberg</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Bundles.20and.20object.20classifiers/near/568571284\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I got a ping that has me worried I asked the question poorly.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I had no idea what the earlier question meant, and got worn out trying to decipher it.  This one looks much clearer, thanks  - though still very open-ended.</p>",
        "id": 568571436,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1768638935
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe they're too open ended because my real goal is broader than exact sequences. I'm trying to understand arrows via fibers.</p>\n<p>If I restrict my attention to Set, and look at a type family <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F : \\mathbb{N} → Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> defined by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(n) = \\{0, 1, \\ldots, n\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">…</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>, then I know the associated projection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>∫</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi : \\int F → \\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span></span></span></span> is surjective, because each set of the family has at least one element.</p>\n<p>I know many properties about functions can be defined in terms of properties of their fibers.</p>\n<p>I'd like to be able to classify morphisms in terms of their fibers in more categories than just set. Which means I need to be able to say stuff about the fibers in categories other than set.</p>\n<p>The way this relates back to my original question, is I think the classifiers can be thought of as structurally encoding requirements on the fibers.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega = \\{ 1, \\{\\} \\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mclose\">}}</span></span></span></span> classifies injections</li>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{ 1 \\} </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> classifies bijections</li>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Set - \\{\\{\\}\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{{</span><span class=\"mclose\">}}</span></span></span></span> \"nonempty sets\", classify surjections</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These are all technically subcategories of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>, so in particular maybe I can find a strategy for relating <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>I'm actually optimistic I'll get more ideas for how to formalize this if I keep reading Weber's paper. So if that's still too open ended, hopefully I'll have a chance to fix it.</p>",
        "id": 568574253,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1768642387
    }
]